C and C++ are weakly typed because you can do things like<p><pre><code>  int x = 42;
  printf("%c\n", *(char *) &x);
</code></pre>
that is, access the underlying bits which represent a value as if they were of some completely different type. The results are deliberately not standardized and vary with your machine. Python doesn't provide any way to do this; at worst you get a TypeError for a conversion that isn't implemented, or AttributeError for a slot that an object doesn't have.<p>Implicitly parsing strings to produce numbers isn't weak typing, merely reckless and prone to mistakes. Weak typing can corrupt the state of your program so severely that even correct code begins to malfunction.
